# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geometric-optics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The **focal length** of an optical system is a measure of how strongly the system converges or diverges light; it has units of length, and for an idealized thin lens is equal to the distance between the lens and its focal points.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] A positive focal length indicates that a system converges light, while a negative focal length indicates that the system diverges light.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] A system with a shorter focal length bends the rays more sharply, bringing them to a focus in a shorter distance or diverging them more quickly.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For the special case of a thin lens in air, a positive focal length is the distance over which initially collimated (parallel) rays are brought to a focus, or alternatively a negative focal length indicates how far in front of the lens a point source must be located to form a collimated beam.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For more general optical systems, the focal length has no intuitive meaning; it is simply the inverse of the system's optical power.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] On the other hand, in applications such as microscopy in which magnification is achieved by bringing the object close to the lens, a shorter focal length (higher optical power) leads to higher magnification because the subject can be brought closer to the center of projection.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For a thin lens in air, the focal length is the distance from the center of the lens to the principal foci (or *focal points*) of the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For a converging lens (for example a convex lens), the focal length is positive and is the distance at which a beam of collimated light will be focused to a single spot.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For a diverging lens (for example a concave lens), the focal length is negative and is the distance to the point from which a collimated beam appears to be diverging after passing through the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The focal length of a thin *convex* lens can be easily measured by using it to form an image of a distant light source on a screen.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The lens is moved until a sharp image is formed on the screen.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Determining the focal length of a *concave* lens is somewhat more difficult.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The focal length of such a lens is defined as the point at which the spreading beams of light meet when they are extended backwards.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] No image is formed during such a test, and the focal length must be determined by passing light (for example, the light of a laser beam) through the lens, examining how much that light becomes dispersed or bent, and following the beam of light backwards to the lens's focal point.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The imaging properties of the optical system can be modeled by replacing the system with an ideal thin lens with the same EFL.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Some authors refer to this as "front focal length".
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Some authors refer to this as "back focal length".
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For an optical system in air or vacuum where the refractive index can be considered 1, the effective focal length, front focal length, and rear focal length are all the same and may be called simply "focal length".
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For an optical system in a medium other than air or vacuum, the front and rear focal lengths are equal to the EFL times the refractive index of the medium in front of or behind the lens (*n*1 and *n*2 in the diagram above).
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The term "focal length" by itself is ambiguous in this case.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The historical usage was to define the "focal length" as the EFL times the index of refraction of the medium.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For a system with different media on both sides, such as the human eye, the front and rear focal lengths are not equal to one another, and convention may dictate which one is called "the focal length" of the system.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Some modern authors avoid this ambiguity by instead defining "focal length" to be a synonym for EFL.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The distinction between front/rear focal length and EFL is important for studying the human eye.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The eye can be represented by an equivalent thin lens at an air/fluid boundary with front and rear focal lengths equal to those of the eye, or it can be represented by a *different* equivalent thin lens that is totally in air, with focal length equal to the eye's EFL.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The quantity ⁠1/*f*⁠ is also known as the optical power of the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] In the sign convention used here, the value of *R*1 will be positive if the first lens surface is convex, and negative if it is concave.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The value of *R*2 is negative if the second surface is convex, and positive if concave.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Sign conventions vary between different authors, which results in different forms of these equations depending on the convention used.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For a spherically-curved mirror in air, the magnitude of the focal length is equal to the radius of curvature of the mirror divided by two.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The focal length is positive for a concave mirror, and negative for a convex mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] where R is the radius of curvature of the mirror's surface.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] See Radius of curvature (optics) for more information on the sign convention for radius of curvature used here.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] An example of how lens choice affects angle of view.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] camera at a fixed distance from the subject.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Camera lens focal lengths are usually specified in millimetres (mm), but some older lenses are marked in centimetres (cm) or inches.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Focal length (f) and field of view (FOV) of a lens are inversely proportional.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For a standard rectilinear lens, ${\textstyle \mathrm {FOV} =2\arctan {\left({x \over 2f}\right)}}$ , where x is the width of the film or imaging sensor.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] When a photographic lens is set to "infinity", its rear principal plane is separated from the sensor or film, which is then situated at the focal plane, by the lens's focal length.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Objects far away from the camera then produce sharp images on the sensor or film, which is also at the image plane.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] To render closer objects in sharp focus, the lens must be adjusted to increase the distance between the rear principal plane and the film, to put the film at the image plane.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] As *s*1 is decreased, *s*2 must be increased.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For example, consider a normal lens for a 35 mm camera with a focal length of *f* = 50 mm.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] To focus a distant object (*s*1 ≈ ∞), the rear principal plane of the lens must be located a distance *s*2 = 50 mm from the film plane, so that it is at the location of the image plane.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] To focus an object 1 m away (*s*1 = 1,000 mm), the lens must be moved 2.6 mm farther away from the film plane, to *s*2 = 52.6 mm.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The focal length of a lens determines the magnification at which it images distant objects.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] It is equal to the distance between the image plane and a pinhole that images distant objects the same size as the lens in question.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For rectilinear lenses (that is, with no image distortion), the imaging of distant objects is well modelled as a pinhole camera model.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] This model leads to the simple geometric model that photographers use for computing the angle of view of a camera; in this case, the angle of view depends only on the ratio of focal length to film size.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] In general, the angle of view depends also on the distortion.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For full-frame 35 mm-format cameras, the diagonal is 43 mm and a typical "normal" lens has a 50 mm focal length.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] A lens with a focal length shorter than normal is often referred to as a wide-angle lens (typically 35 mm and less, for 35 mm-format cameras), while a lens significantly longer than normal may be referred to as a telephoto lens (typically 85 mm and more, for 35 mm-format cameras).
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Technically, long focal length lenses are only "telephoto" if the focal length is longer than the physical length of the lens, but the term is often used to describe any long focal length lens.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Due to the popularity of the 35 mm standard, camera–lens combinations are often described in terms of their 35 mm-equivalent focal length, that is, the focal length of a lens that would have the same angle of view, or field of view, if used on a full-frame 35 mm camera.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Use of a 35 mm-equivalent focal length is particularly common with digital cameras, which often use sensors smaller than 35 mm film, and so require correspondingly shorter focal lengths to achieve a given angle of view, by a factor known as the crop factor.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The optical power of a lens or curved mirror is a physical quantity equal to the reciprocal of the focal length, expressed in metres.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] A dioptre is its unit of measurement with dimension of reciprocal length, equivalent to one reciprocal metre, 1 dioptre = 1 m−1.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] For example, a 2-dioptre lens brings parallel rays of light to focus at 1⁄2 metre.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] A flat window has an optical power of zero dioptres, as it does not cause light to converge or diverge.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] The main benefit of using optical power rather than focal length is that the thin lens formula has the object distance, image distance, and focal length all as reciprocals.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Additionally, when relatively thin lenses are placed close together their powers approximately add.
[src:geometric-optics/focal-length] Thus, a thin 2.0-dioptre lens placed close to a thin 0.5-dioptre lens yields almost the same focal length as a single 2.5-dioptre lens.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Geometrical optics does not account for certain optical effects such as diffraction and interference, which are considered in physical optics.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] This simplification is useful in practice; it is an excellent approximation when the wavelength is small compared to the size of structures with which the light interacts.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The techniques are particularly useful in describing geometrical aspects of imaging, including optical aberrations.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] A light ray is a line or curve that is perpendicular to the light's wavefronts (and is therefore collinear with the wave vector).
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] A slightly more rigorous definition of a light ray follows from Fermat's principle, which states that the path taken between two points by a ray of light is the path that can be traversed in the least time.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Geometrical optics is often simplified by making the paraxial approximation, or "small angle approximation".
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The mathematical behavior then becomes linear, allowing optical components and systems to be described by simple matrices.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] This leads to the techniques of Gaussian optics and *paraxial ray tracing*, which are used to find basic properties of optical systems, such as approximate image and object positions and magnifications.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Glossy surfaces such as mirrors reflect light in a simple, predictable way.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] This allows for production of reflected images that can be associated with an actual (real) or extrapolated (virtual) location in space.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] With such surfaces, the direction of the reflected ray is determined by the angle the incident ray makes with the surface normal, a line perpendicular to the surface at the point where the ray hits.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The incident and reflected rays lie in a single plane, and the angle between the reflected ray and the surface normal is the same as that between the incident ray and the normal.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] For flat mirrors, the law of reflection implies that images of objects are upright and the same distance behind the mirror as the objects are in front of the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The image size is the same as the object size.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] (The magnification of a flat mirror is equal to one.) The law also implies that mirror images are parity inverted, which is perceived as a left-right inversion.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Mirrors with curved surfaces can be modeled by ray tracing and using the law of reflection at each point on the surface.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] For mirrors with parabolic surfaces, parallel rays incident on the mirror produce reflected rays that converge at a common focus.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Other curved surfaces may also focus light, but with aberrations due to the diverging shape causing the focus to be smeared out in space.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] In particular, spherical mirrors exhibit spherical aberration.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Curved mirrors can form images with magnification greater than or less than one, and the image can be upright or inverted.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] An upright image formed by reflection in a mirror is always virtual, while an inverted image is real and can be projected onto a screen.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Refraction occurs when light travels through an area of space that has a changing index of refraction.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The simplest case of refraction occurs when there is an interface between a uniform medium with index of refraction $n_{1}$ and another medium with index of refraction $n_{2}$ .
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] In such situations, Snell's Law describes the resulting deflection of the light ray: $n_{1}\sin \theta _{1}=n_{2}\sin \theta _{2}$ where $\theta _{1}$ and $\theta _{2}$ are the angles between the normal (to the interface) and the incident and refracted waves, respectively.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] This phenomenon is also associated with a changing speed of light as seen from the definition of index of refraction provided above which implies: $v_{1}\sin \theta _{2}\ =v_{2}\sin \theta _{1}$ where $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ are the wave velocities through the respective media.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Various consequences of Snell's Law include the fact that for light rays traveling from a material with a high index of refraction to a material with a low index of refraction, it is possible for the interaction with the interface to result in zero transmission.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] This phenomenon is called total internal reflection and allows for fiber optics technology.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] As light signals travel down a fiber optic cable, they undergo total internal reflection allowing for essentially no light lost over the length of the cable.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] It is also possible to produce polarized light rays using a combination of reflection and refraction: When a refracted ray and the reflected ray form a right angle, the reflected ray has the property of "plane polarization".
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The angle of incidence required for such a scenario is known as Brewster's angle.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Snell's Law can be used to predict the deflection of light rays as they pass through "linear media" as long as the indexes of refraction and the geometry of the media are known.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] For example, the propagation of light through a prism results in the light ray being deflected depending on the shape and orientation of the prism.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Additionally, since different frequencies of light have slightly different indexes of refraction in most materials, refraction can be used to produce dispersion spectra that appear as rainbows.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The discovery of this phenomenon when passing light through a prism is famously attributed to Isaac Newton.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Some media have an index of refraction which varies gradually with position and, thus, light rays curve through the medium rather than travel in straight lines.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] This effect is what is responsible for mirages seen on hot days where the changing index of refraction of the air causes the light rays to bend creating the appearance of specular reflections in the distance (as if on the surface of a pool of water).
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Material that has a varying index of refraction is called a gradient-index (GRIN) material and has many useful properties used in modern optical scanning technologies including photocopiers and scanners.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The phenomenon is studied in the field of gradient-index optics.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] A device which produces converging or diverging light rays due to refraction is known as a lens.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Thin lenses produce focal points on either side that can be modeled using the lensmaker's equation.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] In general, two types of lenses exist: convex lenses, which cause parallel light rays to converge, and concave lenses, which cause parallel light rays to diverge.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The detailed prediction of how images are produced by these lenses can be made using ray-tracing similar to curved mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The focal length f is considered negative for concave lenses.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Incoming parallel rays are focused by a convex lens into an inverted real image one focal length from the lens, on the far side of the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Rays from an object at finite distance are focused further from the lens than the focal distance; the closer the object is to the lens, the further the image is from the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] With concave lenses, incoming parallel rays diverge after going through the lens, in such a way that they seem to have originated at an upright virtual image one focal length from the lens, on the same side of the lens that the parallel rays are approaching on.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Rays from an object at finite distance are associated with a virtual image that is closer to the lens than the focal length, and on the same side of the lens as the object.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The closer the object is to the lens, the closer the virtual image is to the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Likewise, the magnification of a lens is given by $M=-{\frac {S_{2}}{S_{1}}}={\frac {f}{f-S_{1}}}$ where the negative sign is given, by convention, to indicate an upright object for positive values and an inverted object for negative values.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Similar to mirrors, upright images produced by single lenses are virtual while inverted images are real.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Lenses suffer from aberrations that distort images and focal points.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] These are due to both to geometrical imperfections and due to the changing index of refraction for different wavelengths of light (chromatic aberration).
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] As a mathematical study, geometrical optics emerges as a short-wavelength limit for solutions to hyperbolic partial differential equations (Sommerfeld–Runge method) or as a property of propagation of field discontinuities according to Maxwell's equations (Luneburg method).
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] In this short-wavelength limit, it is possible to approximate the solution locally by $u(t,x)\approx a(t,x)e^{i(k\cdot x-\omega t)}$ where $k,\omega$ satisfy a dispersion relation, and the amplitude $a(t,x)$ varies slowly.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] More precisely, the leading order solution takes the form $a_{0}(t,x)e^{i\varphi (t,x)/\varepsilon }.$ The phase $\varphi (t,x)/\varepsilon$ can be linearized to recover large wavenumber $k:=\nabla _{x}\varphi$ , and frequency $\omega :=-\partial _{t}\varphi$ .
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The amplitude $a_{0}$ satisfies a transport equation.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The small parameter $\varepsilon \,$ enters the scene due to highly oscillatory initial conditions.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Thus, when initial conditions oscillate much faster than the coefficients of the differential equation, solutions will be highly oscillatory, and transported along rays.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Assuming coefficients in the differential equation are smooth, the rays will be too.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] In other words, refraction does not take place.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The motivation for this technique comes from studying the typical scenario of light propagation where short wavelength light travels along rays that minimize (more or less) its travel time.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Its full application requires tools from microlocal analysis.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The method of obtaining equations of geometrical optics by taking the limit of zero wavelength was first described by Arnold Sommerfeld and J.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Their derivation was based on an oral remark by Peter Debye.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Here, $n(\mathbf {r} )$ is the refractive index of the medium.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] For large but finite value of $k_{o}$ , the series diverges, and one has to be careful in keeping only appropriate first few terms.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] For each value of $k_{o}$ , one can find an optimum number of terms to be kept and adding more terms than the optimum number might result in a poorer approximation.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The remaining equations determine the functions $A_{m}(\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The method of obtaining equations of geometrical optics by analysing surfaces of discontinuities of solutions to Maxwell's equations was first described by Rudolf Karl Luneburg in 1944.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] This condition is satisfied by e.g. plane waves but is not additive.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] An example of such surface of discontinuity is the initial wave front emanating from a source that starts radiating at a certain instant of time.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Those fields obey transport equations consistent with the transport equations of the Sommerfeld-Runge approach.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Light rays in Luneburg's theory are defined as trajectories orthogonal to the discontinuity surfaces and can be shown to obey Fermat's principle of least time thus establishing the identity of those rays with light rays of standard optics.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The above developments can be generalised to anisotropic media.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] The proof of Luneburg's theorem is based on investigating how Maxwell's equations govern the propagation of discontinuities of solutions.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] And since $\Gamma _{0}$ is arbitrary, the integrands must be equal to 0 which proves the lemma.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] It's now easy to show that as they propagate through a continuous medium, the discontinuity surfaces obey the eikonal equation.
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Specifically, if $\varepsilon$ and $\mu$ are continuous, then the discontinuities of $\mathbf {E}$ and $\mathbf {H}$ satisfy: $[\varepsilon \mathbf {E} ]=\varepsilon [\mathbf {E} ]$ and $[\mu \mathbf {H} ]=\mu [\mathbf {H} ]$ .
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Because of the physical considerations one can assume without loss of generality that $\varphi$ is of the following form: $\varphi (x,y,z,t)=\psi (x,y,z)-ct$ , i.e. a 2D surface moving through space, modelled as level surfaces of $\psi$ .
[src:geometric-optics/geometrical-optics] Other laws of optics like Snell's law and Fresnel formulae can be similarly obtained by considering discontinuities in $\varepsilon$ and $\mu$ .
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A **mirror**, also known as a **looking glass**, is an object that reflects an image.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Light that bounces off a mirror forms an image of whatever is in front of it, which is then focused through the lens of the eye or a camera.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors reverse the direction of light at an angle equal to its incidence.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This allows the viewer to see themselves or objects behind them, or even objects that are at an angle from them but out of their field of view, such as around a corner.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Natural mirrors have existed since prehistoric times, such as the surface of water, but people have been manufacturing mirrors out of a variety of materials for thousands of years, like stone, metals, and glass.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In modern mirrors, metals like silver or aluminium are often used due to their high reflectivity, applied as a thin coating on glass because of its naturally smooth and very hard surface.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Light consists of waves, and when light waves reflect from the flat surface of a mirror, those waves retain the same degree of curvature and vergence, in an equal yet opposite direction, as the original waves.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This allows the waves to form an image when they are focused through a lens, just as if the waves had originated from the direction of the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The light can also be pictured as rays (imaginary lines radiating from the light source, that are always perpendicular to the waves).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These rays are reflected at an equal yet opposite angle from which they strike the mirror (incident light).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This property, called specular reflection, distinguishes a mirror from objects that diffuse light, breaking up the wave and scattering it in many directions (such as flat-white paint).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Thus, a mirror can be any surface in which the texture or roughness of the surface is smaller (smoother) than the wavelength of the waves.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] When looking at a mirror, one will see a mirror image or reflected image of objects in the environment, formed by light emitted or scattered by them and reflected by the mirror towards one's eyes.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This effect gives the illusion that those objects are behind the mirror, or (sometimes) in front of it.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] When the surface is not flat, a mirror may behave like a reflecting lens.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A plane mirror yields a real-looking undistorted image, while a curved mirror may distort, magnify, or reduce the image in various ways, while keeping the lines, contrast, sharpness, colors, and other image properties intact.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A mirror is commonly used for inspecting oneself, such as during personal grooming; hence the old-fashioned name "looking glass".
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This use, which dates from prehistory, overlaps with uses in decoration and architecture.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors are also used to view other items that are not directly visible because of obstructions; examples include rear-view mirrors in vehicles, security mirrors in or around buildings, and dentist's mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors are also used in optical and scientific apparatus such as telescopes, lasers, cameras, periscopes, and industrial machinery.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] According to superstitions breaking a mirror is said to bring seven years of bad luck.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The terms "mirror" and "reflector" can be used for objects that reflect any other types of waves.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] An acoustic mirror reflects sound waves.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Objects such as walls, ceilings, or natural rock-formations may produce echos, and this tendency often becomes a problem in acoustical engineering when designing houses, auditoriums, or recording studios.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Acoustic mirrors may be used for applications such as parabolic microphones, atmospheric studies, sonar, and seafloor mapping.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] An atomic mirror reflects matter waves and can be used for atomic interferometry and atomic holography.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The first mirrors used by humans were most likely pools of still water, or shiny stones.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The requirements for making a good mirror are a surface with a very high degree of flatness (preferably but not necessarily with high reflectivity), and a surface roughness smaller than the wavelength of the light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The earliest manufactured mirrors were pieces of polished stone such as obsidian, a naturally occurring volcanic glass.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Examples of obsidian mirrors found at Çatalhöyük in Anatolia (modern-day Turkey) have been dated to around 6000 BCE.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors of polished copper were crafted in Mesopotamia from 4000 BCE, and in ancient Egypt from around 3000 BCE.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Polished stone mirrors from Central and South America date from around 2000 BCE onwards.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] By the Bronze Age most cultures were using mirrors made from polished discs of bronze, copper, silver, or other metals.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The people of Kerma in Nubia were skilled in the manufacturing of mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Remains of their bronze kilns have been found within the temple of Kerma.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In China, bronze mirrors were manufactured from around 2000 BC, some of the earliest bronze and copper examples being produced by the Qijia culture.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Such metal mirrors remained the norm through to Greco-Roman Antiquity and throughout the Middle Ages in Europe.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] During the Roman Empire silver mirrors were in wide use by servants.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Speculum metal is a highly reflective alloy of copper and tin that was used for mirrors until a couple of centuries ago.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Up until the mid-19th century, many astronomical telescopes used speculum metal mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Isaac Newton's reflecting telescope of 1668 used speculum metal, as did Australia's Great Melbourne Telescope, installed in 1869.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Speculum metal mirrors may have originated in China and India.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors of speculum metal or any precious metal were hard to produce and were only owned by the wealthy.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Common metal mirrors tarnished and required frequent polishing.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Bronze mirrors had low reflectivity and poor color rendering, and stone mirrors were much worse in this regard.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The Greek philosopher Socrates urged young people to look at themselves in mirrors so that, if they were beautiful, they would become worthy of their beauty, and if they were ugly, they would know how to hide their disgrace through learning.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Glass began to be used for mirrors in the 1st century CE, with the development of soda-lime glass and glass blowing.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The Roman scholar Pliny the Elder claims that artisans in Sidon (modern-day Lebanon) were producing glass mirrors coated with lead or gold leaf in the back.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The metal provided good reflectivity, and the glass provided a smooth surface and protected the metal from scratches and tarnishing.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] However, there is no archeological evidence of glass mirrors before the third century.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These early glass mirrors were made by blowing a glass bubble, and then cutting off a small circular section from 10 to 20 cm in diameter.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Their surface was either concave or convex, and imperfections tended to distort the image.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Lead-coated mirrors were very thin to prevent cracking by the heat of the molten metal.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Due to the poor quality, high cost, and small size of glass mirrors, solid-metal mirrors (primarily of steel) remained in common use until the late nineteenth century.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Silver-coated metal mirrors were developed in China as early as 500 CE.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The bare metal was coated with an amalgam, then heated until the mercury boiled away.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The evolution of glass mirrors in the Middle Ages followed improvements in glassmaking technology.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Glassmakers in France made flat glass plates by blowing glass bubbles, spinning them rapidly to flatten them, and cutting rectangles out of them.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A better method, developed in Germany and perfected in Venice by the 16th century, was to blow a cylinder of glass, cut off the ends, slice it along its length, and unroll it onto a flat hot plate.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Venetian glassmakers also adopted lead glass for mirrors, because of its crystal-clarity and its easier workability.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] During the early European Renaissance, a fire-gilding technique developed to produce an even and highly reflective tin coating for glass mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The back of the glass was coated with a tin–mercury amalgam, and the mercury was then evaporated by heating the piece.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This process caused less thermal shock to the glass than the older molten-lead method.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The date and location of the discovery is unknown, but by the 16th century Venice was a center of mirror production using this technique.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These Venetian mirrors were up to 40 inches (100 cm) square.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Venice retained its monopoly on the tin amalgam technique for a century.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Venetian mirrors in richly decorated frames served as luxury decorations for palaces throughout Europe, and were very expensive.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For example, in the late seventeenth century, the Countess de Fiesque was reported to have traded an entire wheat farm for a mirror, considering it a bargain.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] However, by the end of that century the secret was leaked through industrial espionage.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] French workshops succeeded in large-scale industrialization of the process, eventually making mirrors affordable to the masses, in spite of the toxicity of mercury's vapor.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The invention of the ribbon machine in the late Industrial Revolution allowed modern glass panes to be produced in bulk.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The Saint-Gobain factory, founded by royal initiative in France, was an important manufacturer, and Bohemian and German glass, often rather cheaper, was also important.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The invention of the silvered-glass mirror is credited to German chemist Justus von Liebig in 1835.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] His wet deposition process involved the deposition of a thin layer of metallic silver onto glass through the chemical reduction of silver nitrate.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This silvering process was adapted for mass manufacturing and led to the greater availability of affordable mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors are often produced by the wet deposition of silver, or sometimes nickel or chromium (the latter used most often in automotive mirrors) via electroplating directly onto the glass substrate.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Glass mirrors for optical instruments are usually produced by vacuum deposition methods.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These techniques can be traced to observations in the 1920s and 1930s that metal was being ejected from electrodes in gas discharge lamps and condensed on the glass walls forming a mirror-like coating.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The phenomenon, called sputtering, was developed into an industrial metal-coating method with the development of semiconductor technology in the 1970s.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A similar phenomenon had been observed with incandescent light bulbs: the metal in the hot filament would slowly sublimate and condense on the bulb's walls.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This phenomenon was developed into the method of evaporation coating by Pohl and Pringsheim in 1912.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Strong used evaporation coating to make the first aluminium-coated telescope mirrors in the 1930s.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The first dielectric mirror was created in 1937 by Auwarter using evaporated rhodium.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The metal coating of glass mirrors is usually protected from abrasion and corrosion by a layer of paint applied over it.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors for optical instruments often have the metal layer on the front face, so that the light does not have to cross the glass twice.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In these mirrors, the metal may be protected by a thin transparent coating of a non-metallic (dielectric) material.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The first metallic mirror to be enhanced with a dielectric coating of silicon dioxide was created by Hass in 1937.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In 1939 at the Schott Glass company, Walter Geffcken invented the first dielectric mirrors to use multilayer coatings.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The Greek in Classical Antiquity were familiar with the use of mirrors to concentrate light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Parabolic mirrors were described and studied by the mathematician Diocles in his work *On Burning Mirrors*.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Ptolemy conducted a number of experiments with curved polished iron mirrors, and discussed plane, convex spherical, and concave spherical mirrors in his *Optics*.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Parabolic mirrors were also described by the Caliphate mathematician Ibn Sahl in the tenth century.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors can be classified in many ways; including by shape, support, reflective materials, manufacturing methods, and intended application.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Typical mirror shapes are planar and curved mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The surface of curved mirrors is often a part of a sphere.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors that are meant to precisely concentrate parallel rays of light into a point are usually made in the shape of a paraboloid of revolution instead; they are used in telescopes (from radio waves to X-rays), in antennas to communicate with broadcast satellites, and in solar furnaces.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A segmented mirror, consisting of multiple flat or curved mirrors, properly placed and oriented, may be used instead.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors that are intended to concentrate sunlight onto a long pipe may be a circular cylinder or of a parabolic cylinder.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The most common structural material for mirrors is glass, due to its transparency, ease of fabrication, rigidity, hardness, and ability to take a smooth finish.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The most common mirrors consist of a plate of transparent glass, with a thin reflective layer on the back (the side opposite to the incident and reflected light) backed by a coating that protects that layer against abrasion, tarnishing, and corrosion.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The glass is usually soda-lime glass, but lead glass may be used for decorative effects, and other transparent materials may be used for specific applications.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A plate of transparent plastic may be used instead of glass, for lighter weight or impact resistance.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Alternatively, a flexible transparent plastic film may be bonded to the front and/or back surface of the mirror, to prevent injuries in case the mirror is broken.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Lettering or decorative designs may be printed on the front face of the glass, or formed on the reflective layer.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The front surface may have an anti-reflection coating.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors which are reflective on the front surface (the same side of the incident and reflected light) may be made of any rigid material.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The supporting material does not necessarily need to be transparent, but telescope mirrors often use glass anyway.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Often a protective transparent coating is added on top of the reflecting layer, to protect it against abrasion, tarnishing, and corrosion, or to absorb certain wavelengths.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Thin flexible plastic mirrors are sometimes used for safety, since they cannot shatter or produce sharp flakes.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Their flatness is achieved by stretching them on a rigid frame.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These usually consist of a layer of evaporated aluminium between two thin layers of transparent plastic.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In common mirrors, the reflective layer is usually some metal like silver, tin, nickel, or chromium, deposited by a wet process; or aluminium, deposited by sputtering or evaporation in vacuum.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The reflective layer may also be made of one or more layers of transparent materials with suitable indices of refraction.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The structural material may be a metal, in which case the reflecting layer may be just the surface of the same.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Metal concave dishes are often used to reflect infrared light (such as in space heaters) or microwaves (as in satellite TV antennas).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Liquid metal telescopes use a surface of liquid metal such as mercury.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors that reflect only part of the light, while transmitting some of the rest, can be made with very thin metal layers or suitable combinations of dielectric layers.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] They are typically used as beamsplitters.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A dichroic mirror, in particular, has surface that reflects certain wavelengths of light, while letting other wavelengths pass through.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A cold mirror is a dichroic mirror that efficiently reflects the entire visible light spectrum while transmitting infrared wavelengths.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A hot mirror is the opposite: it reflects infrared light while transmitting visible light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Dichroic mirrors are often used as filters to remove undesired components of the light in cameras and measuring instruments.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In X-ray telescopes, the X-rays reflect off a highly precise metal surface at almost grazing angles, and only a small fraction of the rays are reflected.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In flying relativistic mirrors conceived for X-ray lasers, the reflecting surface is a spherical shockwave (wake wave) created in a low-density plasma by a very intense laser-pulse, and moving at an extremely high velocity.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A phase-conjugating mirror uses nonlinear optics to reverse the phase difference between incident beams.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Such mirrors may be used, for example, for coherent beam combination.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The useful applications are self-guiding of laser beams and correction of atmospheric distortions in imaging systems.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] When a sufficiently narrow beam of light is reflected at a point of a locally flat surface, the surface's normal direction ${\vec {n}}$ will be the bisector of the angle formed by the two beams at that point.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This property can be explained by the physics of an electromagnetic plane wave that is incident to a flat surface that is electrically conductive or where the speed of light changes abruptly, as between two materials with different indices of refraction.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] More specifically, a concave parabolic mirror (whose surface is a part of a paraboloid of revolution) will reflect rays that are parallel to its axis into rays that pass through its focus.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Conversely, a parabolic concave mirror will reflect any ray that comes from its focus towards a direction parallel to its axis.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] If a concave mirror surface is a part of a prolate ellipsoid, it will reflect any ray coming from one focus toward the other focus.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A convex parabolic mirror, on the other hand, will reflect rays that are parallel to its axis into rays that seem to emanate from the focus of the surface, behind the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Conversely, it will reflect incoming rays that converge toward that point into rays that are parallel to the axis.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A convex mirror that is part of a prolate ellipsoid will reflect rays that converge towards one focus into divergent rays that seem to emanate from the other focus.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Spherical mirrors do not reflect parallel rays to rays that converge to or diverge from a single point, or vice versa, due to spherical aberration.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] However, this aberration can be sufficiently small if the object image is sufficiently far from the mirror and spans a sufficiently small angle around its axis.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors reflect an image to the observer.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] However, unlike a projected image on a screen, an image does not actually exist on the surface of the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For example, when two people look at each other in a mirror, both see different images on the same surface.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] When the light waves converge through the lens of the eye they interfere with each other to form the image on the surface of the retina, and since both viewers see waves coming from different directions, each sees a different image in the same mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Thus, the images observed in a mirror depend upon the angle of the mirror with respect to the eye.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The angle between the object and the observer is always twice the angle between the eye and the normal, or the direction perpendicular to the surface.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] This allows animals with binocular vision to see the reflected image with depth perception and in three dimensions.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The mirror forms a *virtual image* of whatever is in the opposite angle from the viewer, meaning that objects in the image appear to exist in a direct line of sight—behind the surface of the mirror—at an equal distance from their position in front of the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Objects behind the observer, or between the observer and the mirror, are reflected back to the observer without any actual change in orientation; the light waves are simply reversed in a direction perpendicular to the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] However, when viewer is facing the object and the mirror is at an angle between them, the image appears inverted 180° along the direction of the angle.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Objects viewed in a (plane) mirror will appear laterally inverted (e.g., if one raises one's right hand, the image's left hand will appear to go up in the mirror), but not vertically inverted (in the image a person's head still appears above their body).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] However, a mirror does not actually "swap" left and right any more than it swaps top and bottom.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] To be precise, it reverses the object in the direction perpendicular to the mirror surface (the normal), turning the three dimensional image inside out (the way a glove stripped off the hand can be turned inside out, turning a left-hand glove into a right-hand glove or vice versa).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] When a person raises their left hand, the actual left hand raises in the mirror, but gives the illusion of a right hand raising because the imaginary person in the mirror is literally inside-out, hand and all.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] If the person stands side-on to a mirror, the mirror really does reverse left and right hands, that is, objects that are physically closer to the mirror always appear closer in the virtual image, and objects farther from the surface always appear symmetrically farther away regardless of angle.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Looking at an image of oneself with the front-back axis flipped results in the perception of an image with its left-right axis flipped.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] When reflected in the mirror, a person's right hand remains directly opposite their real right hand, but it is perceived by the mind as the left hand in the image.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] When a person looks into a mirror, the image is actually front-back reversed (inside-out), which is an effect similar to the hollow-mask illusion.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Notice that a mirror image is fundamentally different from the object (inside-out) and cannot be reproduced by simply rotating the object.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] An object and its mirror image are said to be chiral.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For things that may be considered as two-dimensional objects (like text), front-back reversal cannot usually explain the observed reversal.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] An image is a two-dimensional representation of a three-dimensional space, and because it exists in a two-dimensional plane, an image can be viewed from front or back.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In the same way that text on a piece of paper appears reversed if held up to a light and viewed from behind, text held facing a mirror will appear reversed, because the image of the text is still facing away from the observer.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Another way to understand the reversals observed in images of objects that are effectively two-dimensional is that the inversion of left and right in a mirror is due to the way human beings perceive their surroundings.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A person's reflection in a mirror appears to be a real person facing them, but for that person to really face themselves (i.e.: twins) one would have to physically turn and face the other, causing an actual swapping of right and left.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A mirror causes an illusion of left-right reversal because left and right were *not* swapped when the image appears to have turned around to face the viewer.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Likewise, text viewed in a mirror would have to be physically turned around, facing the observer and away from the surface, actually swapping left and right, to be read in the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The reflectivity of a mirror is determined by the percentage of reflected light per the total of the incident light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The reflectivity may vary with wavelength.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] All or a portion of the light not reflected is absorbed by the mirror, while in some cases a portion may also transmit through.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Although some small portion of the light will be absorbed by the coating, the reflectivity is usually higher for first-surface mirrors, eliminating both reflection and absorption losses from the substrate.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The reflectivity is often determined by the type and thickness of the coating.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] When the thickness of the coating is sufficient to prevent transmission, all of the losses occur due to absorption.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Aluminium is harder and more resistant to tarnishing than silver, and will reflect 85 to 90% of the light in the visible to near-ultraviolet range, but experiences a drop in its reflectance between 800 and 900 nm.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Gold is very soft and easily scratched, but does not tarnish.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Gold is greater than 96% reflective to near and far-infrared light between 800 and 12000 nm, but poorly reflects visible light with wavelengths shorter than 600 nm (yellow).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Silver is expensive, soft, and quickly tarnishes, but has the highest reflectivity in the visual to near-infrared of any metal.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Silver can reflect up to 98 or 99% of light to wavelengths as long as 2000 nm, but loses nearly all reflectivity at wavelengths shorter than 350 nm.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Dielectric mirrors can reflect greater than 99.99% of light, but only for a narrow range of wavelengths, ranging from a bandwidth of only 10 nm to as wide as 100 nm for tunable lasers.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] However, dielectric coatings can also enhance the reflectivity of metallic coatings and protect them from scratching or tarnishing.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Dielectric materials are typically very hard and relatively cheap, however the number of coats needed generally makes it an expensive process.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In mirrors with low tolerances, the coating thickness may be reduced to save cost, and simply covered with paint to absorb transmission.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Surface quality, or surface accuracy, measures the deviations from a perfect, ideal surface shape.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Increasing the surface quality reduces distortion, artifacts, and aberration in images, and helps increase coherence, collimation, and reduce unwanted divergence in beams.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For plane mirrors, this is often described in terms of flatness, while other surface shapes are compared to an ideal shape.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The surface quality is typically measured with items like interferometers or optical flats, and are usually measured in wavelengths of light (λ).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These deviations can be much larger or much smaller than the surface roughness.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] A normal household-mirror made with float glass may have flatness tolerances as low as 9–14λ per inch (25.4 mm), equating to a deviation of 5600 through 8800 nanometers from perfect flatness.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Precision ground and polished mirrors intended for lasers or telescopes may have tolerances as high as λ/50 (1/50 of the wavelength of the light, or around 12 nm) across the entire surface.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The surface quality can be affected by factors such as temperature changes, internal stress in the substrate, or even bending effects that occur when combining materials with different coefficients of thermal expansion, similar to a bimetallic strip.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Surface roughness describes the texture of the surface, often in terms of the depth of the microscopic scratches left by the polishing operations.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Surface roughness determines how much of the reflection is specular and how much diffuses, controlling how clear or cloudy the image will be.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For perfectly specular reflection, the surface roughness must be kept smaller than the wavelength of the light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For wavelengths that are approaching or are even shorter than the diameter of the atoms, such as X-rays, specular reflection can only be produced by surfaces that are at a grazing incidence from the rays.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Surface roughness is typically measured in microns, wavelength, or grit size, with ~80,000–100,000 grit or ~½λ–¼λ being "optical quality".
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Transmissivity is determined by the percentage of light transmitted per the incident light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Transmissivity is usually the same from both first and second surfaces.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The combined transmitted and reflected light, subtracted from the incident light, measures the amount absorbed by both the coating and substrate.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For transmissive mirrors, such as one-way mirrors, beam splitters, or laser output couplers, the transmissivity of the mirror is an important consideration.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The transmissivity of metallic coatings are often determined by their thickness.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For precision beam-splitters or output couplers, the thickness of the coating must be kept at very high tolerances to transmit the proper amount of light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For dielectric mirrors, the thickness of the coat must always be kept to high tolerances, but it is often more the number of individual coats that determine the transmissivity.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For the substrate, the material used must also have good transmissivity to the chosen wavelengths.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Glass is a suitable substrate for most visible-light applications, but other substrates such as zinc selenide or synthetic sapphire may be used for infrared or ultraviolet wavelengths.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Wedge errors are caused by the deviation of the surfaces from perfect parallelism.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] An optical wedge is the angle formed between two plane-surfaces (or between the principle planes of curved surfaces) due to manufacturing errors or limitations, causing one edge of the mirror to be slightly thicker than the other.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Nearly all mirrors and optics with parallel faces have some slight degree of wedge, which is usually measured in seconds or minutes of arc.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For first-surface mirrors, wedges can introduce alignment deviations in mounting hardware.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For second-surface or transmissive mirrors, wedges can have a prismatic effect on the light, deviating its trajectory or, to a very slight degree, its color, causing chromatic and other forms of aberration.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In some instances, a slight wedge is desirable, such as in certain laser systems where stray reflections from the uncoated surface are better dispersed than reflected back through the medium.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Surface defects are small-scale, discontinuous imperfections in the surface smoothness.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Surface defects are larger (in some cases much larger) than the surface roughness, but only affect small, localized portions of the entire surface.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These are typically found as scratches, digs, pits (often from bubbles in the glass), sleeks (scratches from prior, larger grit polishing operations that were not fully removed by subsequent polishing grits), edge chips, or blemishes in the coating.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These defects are often an unavoidable side-effect of manufacturing limitations, both in cost and machine precision.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] If kept low enough, in most applications these defects will rarely have any adverse effect, unless the surface is located at an image plane where they will show up directly.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] For applications that require extremely low scattering of light, extremely high reflectance, or low absorption due to high energy levels that could destroy the mirror, such as lasers or Fabry-Perot interferometers, the surface defects must be kept to a minimum.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors are usually manufactured by either polishing a naturally reflective material, such as speculum metal, or by applying a reflective coating to a suitable polished substrate.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In some applications, generally those that are cost-sensitive or that require great durability, such as for mounting in a prison cell, mirrors may be made from a single, bulk material such as polished metal.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] However, metals consist of small crystals (grains) separated by grain boundaries that may prevent the surface from attaining optical smoothness and uniform reflectivity.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] The coating of glass with a reflective layer of a metal is generally called "silvering", even though the metal may not be silver.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Currently the main processes are electroplating, "wet" chemical deposition, and vacuum deposition.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Front-coated metal mirrors achieve reflectivities of 90–95% when new.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Applications requiring higher reflectivity or greater durability, where wide bandwidth is not essential, use dielectric coatings, which can achieve reflectivities as high as 99.997% over a limited range of wavelengths.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Because they are often chemically stable and do not conduct electricity, dielectric coatings are almost always applied by methods of vacuum deposition, and most commonly by evaporation deposition.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Because the coatings are usually transparent, absorption losses are negligible.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Unlike with metals, the reflectivity of the individual dielectric-coatings is a function of Snell's law known as the Fresnel equations, determined by the difference in refractive index between layers.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Therefore, the thickness and index of the coatings can be adjusted to be centered on any wavelength.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Vacuum deposition can be achieved in a number of ways, including sputtering, evaporation deposition, arc deposition, reactive-gas deposition, and ion plating, among many others.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Mirrors can be manufactured to a wide range of engineering tolerances, including reflectivity, surface quality, surface roughness, or transmissivity, depending on the desired application.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] These tolerances can range from wide, such as found in a normal household-mirror, to extremely narrow, like those used in lasers or telescopes.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Tightening the tolerances allows better and more precise imaging or beam transmission over longer distances.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] In imaging systems this can help reduce anomalies (artifacts), distortion or blur, but at a much higher cost.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p01] Where viewing distances are relatively close or high precision is not a concern, wider tolerances can be used to make effective mirrors at affordable costs.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Mirrors are commonly used as aids to personal grooming.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] They may range from small sizes (portable), to the size of a wall that they be affixed to.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] They may be handheld, mobile, fixed or adjustable.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] A classic example of an adjustable mirror is the cheval glass, which the user can tilt.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Convex mirrors provide a wider field of view than flat mirrors, and are often used on vehicles, especially large trucks, to minimize blind spots.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] They are sometimes placed at road junctions, and at corners of sites such as parking lots to allow people to see around corners to avoid crashing into other vehicles or shopping carts.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] They are also sometimes used as part of security systems, so that a single video camera can show more than one angle at a time.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Convex mirrors as decoration are used in interior design to provide a predominantly experiential effect.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Dentists use mouth mirrors or "dental mirrors" to allow indirect vision and lighting within the mouth.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Their reflective surfaces may be either flat or curved.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] to allow vision in tight spaces and around corners in equipment.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Rear-view mirrors are widely used in and on vehicles (such as automobiles, or bicycles), to allow drivers to see other vehicles coming up behind them.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] On rear-view sunglasses, the left end of the left glass and the right end of the right glass work as mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] One-way mirrors (also called two-way mirrors) work by overwhelming dim transmitted light with bright reflected light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] One-way windows can be made to work with polarized light in the laboratory without violating the second law.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] This is an apparent paradox that stumped some great physicists, although it does not allow a practical one-way mirror for use in the real world.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] are one-way devices that are commonly used with lasers.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] With the sun as the light source, a mirror can be used to signal by variations in the orientation of the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The signal can be used over long distances, possibly up to 60 kilometres (37 mi) on a clear day.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Native American tribes and numerous militaries used this technique to transmit information between distant outposts.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Mirrors can also be used to attract the attention of search-and-rescue parties.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Specialized types of daylight signalling mirrors are available and are often included in military survival kits.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Microscopic mirrors are a core element of many of the largest high-definition televisions and video projectors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] A common technology of this type is Texas Instruments' DLP.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] A DLP chip is a postage stamp-sized microchip whose surface is an array of millions of microscopic mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The picture is created as the individual mirrors move to either reflect light toward the projection surface (pixel on), or toward a light-absorbing surface (pixel off).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Other projection technologies involving mirrors include LCoS.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Like a DLP chip, LCoS is a microchip of similar size, but rather than millions of individual mirrors, there is a single mirror that is actively shielded by a liquid crystal matrix with up to millions of pixels.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The picture, formed as light, is either reflected toward the projection surface (pixel on), or absorbed by the activated LCD pixels (pixel off).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] LCoS-based televisions and projectors often use 3 chips, one for each primary color.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Large mirrors are used in rear-projection televisions.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Light (for example from a DLP as discussed above) is "folded" by one or more mirrors so that the television set is compact.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Optical discs are modified mirrors which encode binary data as a series of physical pits and lands on an inner layer between the metal backing and outer plastic surface.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The data is read and decoded by observing distortions in a reflected laser beam caused by the physical variations in the inner layer.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Optical discs typically use aluminum backing like conventional mirrors, though ones with silver and gold backings also exist.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Mirrors are integral parts of a solar power plant.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The one shown in the adjacent picture uses concentrated solar power from an array of parabolic troughs.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Telescopes and other precision instruments use *front silvered* or first surface mirrors, where the reflecting surface is placed on the front (or first) surface of the glass (this eliminates reflection from glass surface ordinary back mirrors have).
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Some of them use silver, but most are aluminium, which is more reflective at short wavelengths than silver.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] All of these coatings are easily damaged and require special handling.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] They reflect 90% to 95% of the incident light when new.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The coatings are typically applied by vacuum deposition.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] A protective overcoat is usually applied before the mirror is removed from the vacuum, because the coating otherwise begins to corrode as soon as it is exposed to oxygen and humidity in air.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] *Front silvered* mirrors have to be resurfaced occasionally to maintain their quality.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] There are optical mirrors such as mangin mirrors that are *second surface mirrors* (reflective coating on the rear surface) as part of their optical designs, usually to correct optical aberrations.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The reflectivity of the mirror coating can be measured using a reflectometer and for a particular metal it will be different for different wavelengths of light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] This is exploited in some optical work to make cold mirrors and hot mirrors.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] A cold mirror is made by using a transparent substrate and choosing a coating material that is more reflective to visible light and more transmissive to infrared light.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] A hot mirror is the opposite, the coating preferentially reflects infrared.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Mirror surfaces are sometimes given thin film overcoatings both to retard degradation of the surface and to increase their reflectivity in parts of the spectrum where they will be used.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] For instance, aluminium mirrors are commonly coated with silicon dioxide or magnesium fluoride.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The reflectivity as a function of wavelength depends on both the thickness of the coating and on how it is applied.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] For scientific optical work, dielectric mirrors are often used.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] These are glass (or sometimes other material) substrates on which one or more layers of dielectric material are deposited, to form an optical coating.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] By careful choice of the type and thickness of the dielectric layers, the range of wavelengths and amount of light reflected from the mirror can be specified.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The best mirrors of this type can reflect >99.999% of the light (in a narrow range of wavelengths) which is incident on the mirror.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] In astronomy, adaptive optics is a technique to measure variable image distortions and adapt a deformable mirror accordingly on a timescale of milliseconds, to compensate for the distortions.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Although most mirrors are designed to reflect visible light, surfaces reflecting other forms of electromagnetic radiation are also called "mirrors".
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The mirrors for other ranges of electromagnetic waves are used in optics and astronomy.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Mirrors for radio waves (sometimes known as reflectors) are important elements of radio telescopes.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Two or more mirrors aligned exactly parallel and facing each other can give an infinite regress of reflections, called an infinity mirror effect.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Tradition states that Archimedes used a large array of mirrors to burn Roman ships during an attack on Syracuse.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] This has never been proven or disproved.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] On the TV show *MythBusters*, a team from MIT tried to recreate the famous "Archimedes Death Ray".
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] They were unsuccessful at starting a fire on a ship.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Previous attempts to set a boat on fire using only the bronze mirrors available in Archimedes' time were unsuccessful, and the time taken to ignite the craft would have made its use impractical, resulting in the *MythBusters* team deeming the myth "busted".
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] It was however found that the mirrors made it very difficult for the passengers of the targeted boat to see; such a scenario could have impeded attackers and have provided the origin of the legend.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Periscopes were used to great effect in war, especially during the World Wars where they were used to peer over the parapet of trenches to ensure that the soldier using the periscope could see safely without the risk of incoming direct fire from other small arms.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Due to its location in a steep-sided valley, the Italian town of Viganella gets no direct sunlight for seven weeks each winter.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] In 2006 a €100,000 computer-controlled mirror, 8×5 m, was installed to reflect sunlight into the town's piazza.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] In early 2007 the similarly situated village of Bondo, Switzerland, was considering applying this solution as well.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] In 2013, mirrors were installed to reflect sunlight into the town square in the Norwegian town of Rjukan.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Mirrors can be used to produce enhanced lighting effects in greenhouses or conservatories.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Mirrors are a popular design-theme in architecture, particularly with late modern and post-modernist high-rise buildings in major cities.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Early examples include the Campbell Center in Dallas, which opened in 1972, and the John Hancock Tower (completed in 1976) in Boston.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] More recently, two skyscrapers designed by architect Rafael Viñoly, the Vdara in Las Vegas and 20 Fenchurch Street in London, have experienced unusual problems due to their concave curved-glass exteriors acting as respectively cylindrical and spherical reflectors for sunlight.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] This building had been nicknamed the "walkie-talkie" because its shape was supposedly similar to a certain model of two-way radio; but after its tendency to overheat surrounding objects became known, the nickname changed to the "walkie-scorchie".
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Painters depicting someone gazing into a mirror often also show the person's reflection.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] This is a kind of abstraction—in most cases the angle of view is such that the person's reflection should not be visible.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Similarly, in movies and still photography an actor or actress is often shown ostensibly looking at him- or herself in a mirror, and yet the reflection faces the camera.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] In reality, the actor or actress sees only the camera and its operator in this case, not their own reflection.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] In the psychology of perception, this is known as the Venus effect.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Contemporary anamorphic artist Jonty Hurwitz uses cylindrical mirrors to project distorted sculptures.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] In the Middle Ages, mirrors existed in various shapes for multiple uses.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Mostly they were used as an accessory for personal hygiene but also as tokens of courtly love, made from ivory in the ivory-carving centers in Paris, Cologne and the Southern Netherlands.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] They also had their uses in religious contexts as they were integrated in a special form of pilgrim badges or pewter/lead mirror boxes From the late 14th century.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Burgundian ducal inventories show us that the dukes owned a mass of mirrors or objects with mirrors, not only with religious iconography or inscriptions, but combined with reliquaries, religious paintings or other objects that were distinctively used for personal piety.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Depicted mirrors – orientated on the physical properties of a real mirror – can be seen as metaphors of knowledge and reflection and are thus able to remind beholders to reflect and get to know themselves.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] The mirror may function simultaneously as a symbol and as a device of a moral appeal.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] That is also the case if it is shown in combination with virtues and vices, a combination which also occurs more frequently in the 15th century: the moralizing layers of mirror metaphors remind the beholder to examine themself thoroughly according to their own virtuous or vicious life.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] This is all the more true if the mirror is combined with iconography of death.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Not only is Death as a corpse or skeleton holding the mirror for the still-living personnel of paintings, illuminations and prints, but the skull appears on the convex surfaces of depicted mirrors, showing the painted and real beholders their future face.
[src:geometric-optics/mirror-p02] Only a few animal species have been shown to have the ability to recognize themselves in a mirror, most of them mammals.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] In optics, **aberration** is a property of optical systems, such as lenses and mirrors, that causes the *image* created by the optical system to not be a faithful reproduction of the *object* being observed.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Aberrations cause the image formed by a lens to be blurred, distorted in shape or have color fringing or other effects not seen in the object, with the nature of the distortion depending on the type of aberration.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Aberration can be defined as a departure of the performance of an optical system from the predictions of paraxial optics.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] In an imaging system, it occurs when light from one point of an object does not converge into (or does not diverge from) a single point after transmission through the system.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Aberrations occur because the simple paraxial theory is not a completely accurate model of the effect of an optical system on light, rather than due to flaws in the optical elements.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] An image-forming optical system with aberration will produce an image which is not sharp.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Makers of optical instruments need to correct optical systems to compensate for aberration.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Aberration can be analyzed with the techniques of geometrical optics.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The articles on reflection, refraction and caustics discuss the general features of reflected and refracted rays.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] With an ideal lens, light from any given point on an object would pass through the lens and come together at a single point in the *image plane* (or, more generally, the *image surface*).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Real lenses, even when they are perfectly made, do not however focus light exactly to a single point.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] These deviations from the idealized lens performance are called *aberrations* of the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Aberrations fall into two classes: *monochromatic* and *chromatic*.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Monochromatic aberrations are caused by the geometry of the lens or mirror and occur both when light is reflected and when it is refracted.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] They appear even when using monochromatic light, hence the name.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Chromatic aberrations are caused by dispersion, the variation of a lens's refractive index with wavelength.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Because of dispersion, different wavelengths of light come to focus at different points.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Chromatic aberration does not appear when monochromatic light is used.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Although defocus is technically the lowest-order of the optical aberrations, it is usually not considered as a lens aberration, since it can be corrected by moving the lens (or the image plane) to bring the image plane to the optical focus of the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] In addition to these aberrations, piston and tilt are effects which shift the position of the focal point.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Piston and tilt are not true optical aberrations, since when an otherwise perfect wavefront is altered by piston and tilt, it will still form a perfect, aberration-free image, only shifted to a different position.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Chromatic aberration occurs when different wavelengths are not focussed to the same point.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] These authors showed, however, that no optical system can justify these suppositions, since they are contradictory to the fundamental laws of reflection and refraction.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Consequently, the Gaussian theory only supplies a convenient method of approximating reality; realistic optical systems fall short of this unattainable ideal.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Currently, all that can be accomplished is the projection of a single plane onto another plane; but even in this, aberrations always occurs and it may be unlikely that these will ever be entirely corrected.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Let S (**Figure 1**) be any optical system, rays proceeding from an axis point O under an angle *u*1 will unite in the axis point *O′*1; and those under an angle *u*2 in the axis point *O′*2.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If there is refraction at a collective spherical surface, or through a thin positive lens, *O′*2 will lie in front of *O′*1 so long as the angle *u*2 is greater than *u*1 (*under correction*); and conversely with a dispersive surface or lenses (*over correction*).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The caustic, in the first case, resembles the sign '>' (greater than); in the second '<' (less than).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If the angle *u*1 is very small, *O′*1 is the Gaussian image; and *O′*1 *O′*2 is termed the *longitudinal aberration*, and *O′*1*R* the *lateral aberration* of the pencils with aperture *u*2.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The largest opening of the pencils, which take part in the reproduction of O, i.e., the angle u, is generally determined by the margin of one of the lenses or by a hole in a thin plate placed between, before, or behind the lenses of the system.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This hole is termed the *stop* or *diaphragm*; Abbe used the term *aperture stop* for both the hole and the limiting margin of the lens.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The component *S*1 of the system, situated between the aperture stop and the object O, projects an image of the diaphragm, termed by Abbe the *entrance pupil*; the *exit pupil* is the image formed by the component *S*2, which is placed behind the aperture stop.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] All rays which issue from O and pass through the aperture stop also pass through the entrance and exit pupils, since these are images of the aperture stop.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Since the maximum aperture of the pencils issuing from O is the angle u subtended by the entrance pupil at this point, the magnitude of the aberration will be determined by the position and diameter of the entrance pupil.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If the system be entirely behind the aperture stop, then this is itself the entrance pupil (*front stop*); if entirely in front, it is the exit pupil (*back stop*).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If the object point be infinitely distant, all rays received by the first member of the system are parallel, and their intersections, after traversing the system, vary according to their *perpendicular height of incidence,* i.e. their distance from the axis.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This distance replaces the angle u in the preceding considerations; and the aperture, i.e., the radius of the entrance pupil, is its maximum value.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If rays issuing from O (**Figure 1**) are concurrent, it does not follow that points in a portion of a plane perpendicular at O to the axis will be also concurrent, even if the part of the plane be very small.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] As the diameter of the lens increases (i.e., with increasing aperture), the neighboring point N will be reproduced, but attended by aberrations comparable in magnitude to ON.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] These aberrations are avoided if, according to Abbe, the *sine condition*, sin *u′*1/sin *u*1 = sin *u′*2/sin *u*2, holds for all rays reproducing the point O.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If the object point O is infinitely distant, *u*1 and *u*2 are to be replaced by *h*1 and *h*2, the perpendicular heights of incidence; the *sine condition* then becomes sin *u′*1/*h*1 = sin *u′*2/*h*2.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] A system fulfilling this condition and free from spherical aberration is called *aplanatic* (Greek *a-*, privative; *plann*, a wandering).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This word was first used by Robert Blair to characterize a superior achromatism, and, subsequently, by many writers to denote freedom from spherical aberration as well.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] It is seen (ignoring exceptional cases) that the pencil does not meet the refracting or reflecting surface at right angles; therefore it is astigmatic (Greek *a-*, privative; *stigmia*, a point).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The interval O′O″, termed the astigmatic difference, increases, in general, with the angle W made by the principal ray OP with the axis of the system, i.e. with the field of view.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Two *astigmatic image surfaces* correspond to one object plane; and these are in contact at the axis point; on the one lie the focal lines of the first kind, on the other those of the second.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Systems in which the two astigmatic surfaces coincide are termed anastigmatic or stigmatic.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Sir Isaac Newton was probably the discoverer of astigmation; the position of the astigmatic image lines was determined by Thomas Young; and the theory was developed by Allvar Gullstrand.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Culmann is given in Moritz von Rohr's *Die Bilderzeugung in optischen Instrumenten*.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] By opening the stop wider, similar deviations arise for lateral points as have been already discussed for axial points; but in this case they are much more complicated.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The unsymmetrical form of the meridional pencil – formerly the only one considered – is coma in the narrower sense only; other errors of coma have been treated by Arthur König and Moritz von Rohr, and later by Allvar Gullstrand.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If the above errors be eliminated, the two astigmatic surfaces united, and a sharp image obtained with a wide aperture—there remains the necessity to correct the curvature of the image surface, especially when the image is to be received upon a plane surface, e.g. in photography.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] In most cases the surface is concave towards the system.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Even if the image is sharp, it may be distorted compared to ideal pinhole projection.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] In pinhole projection, the magnification of an object is inversely proportional to its distance to the camera along the optical axis so that a camera pointing directly at a flat surface reproduces that flat surface.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Distortion can be thought of as stretching the image non-uniformly, or, equivalently, as a variation in magnification across the field.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] While "distortion" can include arbitrary deformation of an image, the most pronounced modes of distortion produced by conventional imaging optics is "barrel distortion", in which the center of the image is magnified more than the perimeter (**Figure 3a**).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The reverse, in which the perimeter is magnified more than the center, is known as "pincushion distortion" (**Figure 3b**).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This effect is called lens distortion or image distortion, and there are algorithms to correct it.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Systems free of distortion are called *orthoscopic* (*orthos*, right; *skopein*, to look) or *rectilinear* (straight lines).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This aberration is quite distinct from that of the sharpness of reproduction; in unsharp, reproduction, the question of distortion arises if only parts of the object can be recognized in the figure.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If, in an unsharp image, a patch of light corresponds to an object point, the *center of gravity* of the patch may be regarded as the image point, this being the point where the plane receiving the image, e.g., a focusing screen, intersects the ray passing through the middle of the stop.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This assumption is justified if a poor image on the focusing screen remains stationary when the aperture is diminished; in practice, this generally occurs.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This ray, named by Abbe a *principal ray* (not to be confused with the *principal rays* of the Gaussian theory), passes through the center of the entrance pupil before the first refraction, and the center of the exit pupil after the last refraction.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] From this it follows that correctness of drawing depends solely upon the principal rays; and is independent of the sharpness or curvature of the image field.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Referring to **Figure 4**, we have *O′Q′*/*OQ* = (*a′* tan *w′*)/(*a* tan *w*) = 1/*N*, where N is the *scale* or magnification of the image.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] For N to be constant for all values of w, (*a′* tan *w′*)/(*a* tan *w*) must also be constant.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] If the ratio *a′*/*a* be sufficiently constant, as is often the case, the above relation reduces to the *condition of Airy,* i.e. tan *w′*/tan *w* is a constant.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The constancy of *a′*/*a* necessary for this relation to hold was pointed out by R.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Photog., 1861), and Thomas Sutton (Photographic Notes, 1862); it has been treated by O.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] It requires the middle of the aperture stop to be reproduced in the centers of the entrance and exit pupils without spherical aberration.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] M. von Rohr showed that for systems fulfilling neither the Airy nor the Bow-Sutton condition, the ratio (*a′* cos *w′*)/(*a* tan *w*) will be constant for one distance of the object.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This combined condition is exactly fulfilled by holosymmetrical objectives reproducing with the scale 1, and by hemisymmetrical, if the scale of reproduction be equal to the ratio of the sizes of the two components.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Circular wavefront profiles associated with aberrations may be mathematically modeled using Zernike polynomials.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Developed by Frits Zernike in the 1930s, Zernike's polynomials are orthogonal over a circle of unit radius.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] A complex, aberrated wavefront profile may be curve-fitted with Zernike polynomials to yield a set of fitting coefficients that individually represent different types of aberrations.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] These Zernike coefficients are linearly independent, thus individual aberration contributions to an overall wavefront may be isolated and quantified separately.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] There are even and odd Zernike polynomials.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] where m and n are nonnegative integers with *n* ≥ *m*, ϕ is the azimuthal angle in radians, and ρ is the normalized radial distance.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] where ρ is the normalized pupil radius with 0 ≤ *ρ* ≤ 1, ϕ is the azimuthal angle around the pupil with 0 ≤ *ϕ* ≤ 2*π*, and the fitting coefficients *a*0, ..., *a*8 are the wavefront errors in wavelengths.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] As in Fourier synthesis using sines and cosines, a wavefront may be perfectly represented by a sufficiently large number of higher-order Zernike polynomials.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] However, wavefronts with very steep gradients or very high spatial frequency structure, such as produced by propagation through atmospheric turbulence or aerodynamic flowfields, are not well modeled by Zernike polynomials, which tend to low-pass filter fine spatial definition in the wavefront.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] In this case, other fitting methods such as fractals or singular value decomposition may yield improved fitting results.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The circle polynomials were introduced by Frits Zernike to evaluate the point image of an aberrated optical system taking into account the effects of diffraction.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The perfect point image in the presence of diffraction had already been described by Airy, as early as 1835.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] It took almost hundred years to arrive at a comprehensive theory and modeling of the point image of aberrated systems (Zernike and Nijboer).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The analysis by Nijboer and Zernike describes the intensity distribution close to the optimum focal plane.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] An extended theory that allows the calculation of the point image amplitude and intensity over a much larger volume in the focal region was recently developed (Extended Nijboer-Zernike theory).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This Extended Nijboer-Zernike theory of point image or 'point-spread function' formation has found applications in general research on image formation, especially for systems with a high numerical aperture, and in characterizing optical systems with respect to their aberrations.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] In the mathematical sense, however, this selection is arbitrary; the reproduction of a finite object with a finite aperture entails, in all probability, an infinite number of aberrations.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This number is only finite if the object and aperture are assumed to be *infinitely small of a certain order*; and with each order of infinite smallness, i.e. with each degree of approximation to reality (to finite objects and apertures), a certain number of aberrations is associated.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This connection is only supplied by theories which treat aberrations generally and analytically by means of indefinite series.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] A ray proceeding from an object point O (**Figure 5**) can be defined by the coordinates (*ξ*, *η*).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Of this point O in an object plane I, at right angles to the axis, and two other coordinates (*x*, *y*), the point in which the ray intersects the entrance pupil, i.e. the plane II.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Similarly the corresponding image ray may be defined by the points (*ξ′*, *η′*), and (*x′*, *y′*), in the planes I′ and II′.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The origins of these four plane coordinate systems may be collinear with the axis of the optical system; and the corresponding axes may be parallel.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The nature of the reproduction consists in the rays proceeding from a point O being united in another point O′; in general, this will not be the case, for ξ′, η′ vary if ξ, η be constant, but x, y variable.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Writing Δ*ξ*′ = *ξ*′ − *ξ*′0 and Δ*η*′ = *η*′ − *η*′0, then Δ*ξ*′ and Δ*η*′ are the aberrations belonging to ξ, η and x, y, and are functions of these magnitudes which, when expanded in series, contain only odd powers, for the same reasons as given above.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] On account of the aberrations of all rays which pass through O, a patch of light, depending in size on the lowest powers of ξ, η, x, y which the aberrations contain, will be formed in the plane I′.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Petzval *the numerical orders of the image*, are consequently only odd powers; the condition for the formation of an image of the mth order is that in the series for Δ*ξ*′ and Δ*η*′ the coefficients of the powers of the 3rd, 5th, ...
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The images of the Gauss theory being of the third order, the next problem is to obtain an image of 5th order, or to make the coefficients of the powers of 3rd degree zero.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] This necessitates the satisfying of five equations; in other words, there are five alterations of the 3rd order, the vanishing of which produces an image of the 5th order.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The expression for these coefficients in terms of the constants of the optical system, i.e. the radii, thicknesses, refractive indices and distances between the lenses, was solved by L. von Seidel; in 1840, J.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Petzval constructed his portrait objective, from similar calculations which have never been published.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Finterswalder, who also published a posthumous paper of Seidel containing a short view of his work; a simpler form was given by A.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Konig and M. von Rohr have represented Kerber's method, and have deduced the Seidel formulae from geometrical considerations based on the Abbe method, and have interpreted the analytical results geometrically.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] William Rowan Hamilton thus derived the aberrations of the third order; and in later times the method was pursued by Clerk Maxwell (*Proc.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] 410), and particularly successfully by K.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] 1), who thus discovered the aberrations of the 5th order (of which there are nine), and possibly the shortest proof of the practical (Seidel) formulae.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] 941) founded his theory of aberrations on the differential geometry of surfaces.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The classical imaging problem is to reproduce perfectly a finite plane (the object) onto another plane (the image) through a finite aperture.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] It is impossible to do so perfectly for *more than one* such pair of planes; this was proven with increasing generality by Maxwell in 1858, by Bruns in 1895, and by Carathéodory in 1926, see summary by Walther.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] For a single pair of planes (e.g. for a single focus setting of an objective), however, the problem can in principle be solved perfectly.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Examples of such a theoretically perfect system include the Luneburg lens and the Maxwell fish-eye.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Practical methods solve this problem with an accuracy which mostly suffices for the special purpose of each species of instrument.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Solutions, however, have been obtained in special cases.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] At the present time constructors almost always employ the inverse method: they compose a system from certain, often quite personal experiences, and test, by the trigonometrical calculation of the paths of several rays, whether the system gives the desired reproduction (examples are given in A.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Gleichen, *Lehrbuch der geometrischen Optik*, Leipzig and Berlin, 1902).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The radii, thicknesses and distances are continually altered until the errors of the image become sufficiently small.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] By this method only certain errors of reproduction are investigated, especially individual members, or all, of those named above.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The analytical approximation theory is often employed provisionally, since its accuracy does not generally suffice.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The rays with an angle of aperture smaller than u* would not have the same distance of intersection and the same sine ratio; these deviations are called *zones,* and the constructor endeavors to reduce these to a minimum.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The same holds for the errors depending upon the angle of the field of view, w: astigmatism, curvature of field and distortion are eliminated for a definite value, w*, *zones of astigmatism, curvature of field and distortion,* attend smaller values of w.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] The final form of a practical system consequently rests on compromise; enlargement of the aperture results in a diminution of the available field of view, and vice versa.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] But the larger aperture will give the larger resolution.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Wide angle lens; necessary corrections are — for astigmatism, curvature of field and distortion; errors of the aperture only slightly regarded; examples — photographic widest angle objectives and oculars.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Between these extreme examples stands the normal lens: this is corrected more with regard to aperture; objectives for groups more with regard to the field of view.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Long focus lenses have small fields of view and aberrations on axis are very important.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Therefore, zones will be kept as small as possible and design should emphasize simplicity.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p01] Because of this these lenses are the best for analytical computation.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In optical systems composed of lenses, the position, magnitude and errors of the image depend upon the refractive indices of the glass employed (see Lens (optics) and Monochromatic aberration, above).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] If mixed light be employed (e.g. white light) all these images are formed and they cause a confusion, named chromatic aberration; for instance, instead of a white margin on a dark background, there is perceived a colored margin, or narrow spectrum.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] The absence of this error is termed achromatism, and an optical system so corrected is termed achromatic.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] These constants are determined by the data of the system (radii, thicknesses, distances, indices, etc., of the lenses); therefore their dependence on the refractive index, and consequently on the color, are calculable.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] The refractive indices for different wavelengths must be known for each kind of glass made use of.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In this manner the conditions are maintained that any one constant of reproduction is equal for two different colors, i.e. this constant is achromatized.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] For example, it is possible, with one thick lens in air, to achromatize the position of a focal plane of the magnitude of the focal length.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In practice it is more advantageous (after Abbe) to determine the chromatic aberration (for instance, that of the distance of intersection) for a fixed position of the object, and express it by a sum in which each component conlins the amount due to each refracting surface.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In a plane containing the image point of one color, another colour produces a disk of confusion; this is similar to the confusion caused by two *zones* in spherical aberration.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Newton failed to perceive the existence of media of different dispersive powers required by achromatism; consequently he constructed large reflectors instead of refractors.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] James Gregory and Leonhard Euler arrived at the correct view from a false conception of the achromatism of the eye; this was determined by Chester More Hall in 1728, Klingenstierna in 1754 and by Dollond in 1757, who constructed the celebrated achromatic telescopes.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Glass with weaker dispersive power (greater v ) is named *crown glass*; that with greater dispersive power, *flint glass*.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] For an achromatic dispersive lens the converse must be adopted.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] This is, at the present day, the ordinary type, e.g., of telescope objective; the values of the four radii must satisfy the equations (2) and (4).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Two other conditions may also be postulated: one is always the elimination of the aberration on the axis; the second either the *Herschel* or *Fraunhofer Condition,* the latter being the best vide supra, *Monochromatic Aberration*).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In practice, however, it is often more useful to avoid the second condition by making the lenses have contact, i.e. equal radii.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In all earlier kinds of glass, however, the dispersive power increased with the refractive index; that is, v decreased as n increased; but some of the Jena glasses by E.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Schott were crown glasses of high refractive index, and achromatic systems from such crown glasses, with flint glasses of lower refractive index, are called the *new achromats,* and were employed by P.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Rudolph in the first *anastigmats* (photographic objectives).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Instead of making $df$ vanish, a certain value can be assigned to it which will produce, by the addition of the two lenses, any desired chromatic deviation, e.g. sufficient to eliminate one present in other parts of the system.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] If the lenses I. and II. be cemented and have the same refractive index for one color, then its effect for that one color is that of a lens of one piece; by such decomposition of a lens it can be made chromatic or achromatic at will, without altering its spherical effect.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] If a constant of reproduction, for instance the focal length, be made equal for two colors, then it is not the same for other colors, if two different glasses are employed.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] For example, the condition for achromatism (4) for two thin lenses in contact is fulfilled in only one part of the spectrum, since $dn_{2}/dn_{1}$ varies within the spectrum.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Fraunhofer, who defined the colors by means of the dark lines in the solar spectrum; and showed that the ratio of the dispersion of two glasses varied about 20% from the red to the violet (the variation for glass and water is about 50%).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] These chromatic errors of systems, which are achromatic for two colors, are called the *secondary spectrum,* and depend upon the aperture and focal length in the same manner as the primary chromatic errors do.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In **Figure 6**, taken from M. von Rohr's *Theorie und Geschichte des photographischen Objectivs*, the abscissae are focal lengths, and the ordinates wavelengths.
