[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] The focal lengths are made equal for the lines C and F.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In the neighborhood of 550 nm the tangent to the curve is parallel to the axis of wavelengths; and the focal length varies least over a fairly large range of color, therefore in this neighborhood the color union is at its best.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Moreover, this region of the spectrum is that which appears brightest to the human eye, and consequently this curve of the secondary on spectrum, obtained by making $f_{C}=f_{F}$ , is, according to the experiments of Sir G.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Soc., 1878), the most suitable for visual instruments (*optical achromatism,*).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In a similar manner, for systems used in photography, the vertex of the color curve must be placed in the position of the maximum sensibility of the plates; this is generally supposed to be at G'; and to accomplish this the F and violet mercury lines are united.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] This artifice is specially adopted in objectives for astronomical photography (*pure actinic achromatism*).
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] For ordinary photography, however, there is this disadvantage: the image on the focusing-screen and the correct adjustment of the photographic sensitive plate are not in register; in astronomical photography this difference is constant, but in other kinds it depends on the distance of the objects.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Should there be in two lenses in contact the same focal lengths for three colours a, b, and c, i.e. $f_{a}=f_{b}=f_{c}=f$ , then the relative partial dispersion $(n_{c}-n_{b})(n_{a}-n_{b})$ must be equal for the two kinds of glass employed.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] This follows by considering equation (4) for the two pairs of colors ac and bc.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Until recently no glasses were known with a proportional degree of absorption; but R.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Archer overcame the difficulty by constructing fluid lenses between glass walls.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Fraunhofer prepared glasses which reduced the secondary spectrum; but permanent success was only assured on the introduction of the Jena glasses by E.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In using glasses not having proportional dispersion, the deviation of a third colour can be eliminated by two lenses, if an interval be allowed between them; or by three lenses in contact, which may not all consist of the old glasses.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] In uniting three colors an *achromatism of a higher order* is derived; there is yet a residual *tertiary spectrum,* but it can always be neglected.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] The Gaussian theory is only an approximation; monochromatic or spherical aberrations still occur, which will be different for different colors; and should they be compensated for one color, the image of another color would prove disturbing.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] The most important is the chromatic difference of aberration of the axis point, which is still present to disturb the image, after par-axial rays of different colors are united by an appropriate combination of glasses.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] This error was treated by Jean le Rond d'Alembert, and, in special detail, by C.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] The condition for the reproduction of a surface element in the place of a sharply reproduced point — the constant of the sine relationship must also be fulfilled with large apertures for several colors.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] Abbe succeeded in computing microscope objectives free from error of the axis point and satisfying the sine condition for several colors, which therefore, according to his definition, were *aplanatic for several colors*; such systems he termed *apochromatic*.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] While, however, the magnification of the individual zones is the same, it is not the same for red as for blue; and there is a chromatic difference of magnification.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] This is produced in the same amount, but in the opposite sense, by the oculars, which Abbe used with these objectives (*compensating oculars*), so that it is eliminated in the image of the whole microscope.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] The best telescope objectives, and photographic objectives intended for three-color work, are also apochromatic, even if they do not possess quite the same quality of correction as microscope objectives do.
[src:geometric-optics/optical-aberration-p02] The chromatic differences of other errors of reproduction seldom have practical importance.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] In optics, a **ray** is an idealized geometrical model of light or other electromagnetic radiation, obtained by choosing a curve that is perpendicular to the *wavefronts* of the actual light, and that points in the direction of energy flow.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Rays are used to model the propagation of light through an optical system, by dividing the real light field up into discrete rays that can be computationally propagated through the system by the techniques of *ray tracing*.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] This allows even very complex optical systems to be analyzed mathematically or simulated by computer.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Ray tracing uses approximate solutions to Maxwell's equations that are valid as long as the light waves propagate through and around objects whose dimensions are much greater than the light's wavelength.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] *Ray optics* or *geometrical optics* does not describe phenomena such as diffraction, which require wave optics theory.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Some wave phenomena such as interference can be modeled in limited circumstances by adding phase to the ray model.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] A light ray is a line (straight or curved) that is perpendicular to the light's wavefronts; its tangent is collinear with the wave vector.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Light rays in homogeneous media are straight.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] They bend at the interface between two dissimilar media and may be curved in a medium in which the refractive index changes.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Geometric optics describes how rays propagate through an optical system.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Objects to be imaged are treated as collections of independent point sources, each producing spherical wavefronts and corresponding outward rays.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Rays from each object point can be mathematically propagated to locate the corresponding point on the image.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] There are many special rays that are used in optical modelling to analyze an optical system.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] These are defined and described below, grouped by the type of system they are used to model.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Geometrical optics, or ray optics, is a model of optics that describes light propagation in terms of *rays*.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] The ray in geometrical optics is an abstraction useful for approximating the paths along which light propagates under certain circumstances.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] In physics, ray tracing is a method for calculating the path of waves or particles through a system with regions of varying propagation velocity, absorption characteristics, and reflecting surfaces.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Under these circumstances, wavefronts may bend, change direction, or reflect off surfaces, complicating analysis.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Historically, ray tracing involved analytic solutions to the ray's trajectories.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] In modern applied physics and engineering physics, the term also encompasses numerical solutions to the Eikonal equation.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] For example, ray-marching involves repeatedly advancing idealized narrow beams called *rays* through the medium by discrete amounts.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Simple problems can be analyzed by propagating a few rays using simple mathematics.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] More detailed analysis can be performed by using a computer to propagate many rays.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] When applied to problems of electromagnetic radiation, ray tracing often relies on approximate solutions to Maxwell's equations such as geometric optics, that are valid as long as the light waves propagate through and around objects whose dimensions are much greater than the light's wavelength.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] Ray theory can describe interference by accumulating the phase during ray tracing (e.g., complex-valued Fresnel coefficients and Jones calculus).
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] It can also be extended to describe edge diffraction, with modifications such as the geometric theory of diffraction, which enables tracing *diffracted rays*.
[src:geometric-optics/ray-optics] More complicated phenomena require methods such as physical optics or wave theory.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] In physics, **total internal reflection** (**TIR**) is the phenomenon in which waves arriving at the interface (boundary) from one medium to another (e.g., from water to air) are not refracted into the second ("external") medium, but completely reflected back into the first ("internal") medium.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] It occurs when the second medium has a higher wave speed (i.e., lower refractive index) than the first, and the waves are incident at a sufficiently oblique angle on the interface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For example, the water-to-air surface in a typical fish tank, when viewed obliquely from below, reflects the underwater scene like a mirror with no loss of brightness (Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] A scenario opposite to TIR, referred to as total external reflection, occurs in the extreme ultraviolet and X-ray regimes.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] TIR occurs not only with electromagnetic waves such as light and microwaves, but also with other types of waves, including sound and water waves.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] If the waves are capable of forming a narrow beam (Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] 2), the reflection tends to be described in terms of "rays" rather than waves; in a medium whose properties are independent of direction, such as air, water or glass, the "rays" are perpendicular to associated wavefronts.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The total internal reflection occurs when critical angle is exceeded.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Refraction is generally accompanied by *partial* reflection.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] As the angle of incidence approaches a certain threshold, called the *critical angle*, the angle of refraction approaches 90°, at which the refracted ray becomes parallel to the boundary surface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] As the angle of incidence increases beyond the critical angle, the conditions of refraction can no longer be satisfied, so there is no refracted ray, and the partial reflection becomes total.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For visible light, the critical angle is about 49° for incidence from water to air, and about 42° for incidence from common glass to air.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Details of the mechanism of TIR give rise to more subtle phenomena.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] While total reflection, by definition, involves no continuing flow of power *across* the interface between the two media, the external medium carries a so-called *evanescent wave*, which travels *along* the interface with an amplitude that falls off exponentially with distance from the interface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Unlike *partial* reflection between transparent media, total internal reflection is accompanied by a non-trivial phase shift (not just zero or 180°) for each component of polarization (perpendicular or parallel to the plane of incidence), and the shifts vary with the angle of incidence.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The explanation of this effect by Augustin-Jean Fresnel, in 1823, added to the evidence in favor of the wave theory of light.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The phase shifts are used by Fresnel's invention, the Fresnel rhomb, to modify polarization.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The efficiency of the total internal reflection is exploited by optical fibers (used in telecommunications cables and in image-forming fiberscopes), and by reflective prisms, such as image-erecting Porro/roof prisms for monoculars and binoculars.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Although total internal reflection can occur with any kind of wave that can be said to have oblique incidence, including (e.g.) microwaves and sound waves, it is most familiar in the case of light waves.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Total internal reflection of light can be demonstrated using a semicircular-cylindrical block of common glass or acrylic glass.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] 3, a "ray box" projects a narrow beam of light (a "ray") radially inward.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The semicircular cross-section of the glass allows the incoming ray to remain perpendicular to the curved portion of the air/glass surface, and then hence to continue in a straight line towards the flat part of the surface, although its angle with the flat part varies.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Where the ray meets the flat glass-to-air interface, the angle between the ray and the normal (perpendicular) to the interface is called the *angle of incidence*.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] If this angle is sufficiently small, the ray is *partly* reflected but mostly transmitted, and the transmitted portion is refracted away from the normal, so that the *angle of refraction* (between the refracted ray and the normal to the interface) is greater than the angle of incidence.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For the moment, let us call the angle of incidence *θ*i and the angle of refraction *θ*t (where *t* is for *transmitted*, reserving *r* for *reflected*).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] As *θ*i increases and approaches a certain "critical angle", denoted by *θ*c (or sometimes *θ*cr), the angle of refraction approaches 90° (that is, the refracted ray approaches a tangent to the interface), and the refracted ray becomes fainter while the reflected ray becomes brighter.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] As *θ*i increases beyond *θ*c, the refracted ray disappears and only the reflected ray remains, so that all of the energy of the incident ray is reflected; this is total internal reflection (TIR).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The critical angle is the smallest angle of incidence that yields total reflection, or equivalently the largest angle for which a refracted ray exists.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For light waves incident from an "internal" medium with a single refractive index *n*1, to an "external" medium with a single refractive index *n*2, the critical angle is given by $\theta _{\text{c}}=\arcsin(n_{2}/n_{1})$ and is defined if *n*2 ≤ *n*1.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For some other types of waves, it is more convenient to think in terms of propagation velocities rather than refractive indices.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The explanation of the critical angle in terms of velocities is more general and will therefore be discussed first.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] When a wavefront is refracted from one medium to another, the incident (incoming) and refracted (outgoing) portions of the wavefront meet at a common line on the refracting surface (interface).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Let this line, denoted by *L*, move at velocity u across the surface, where u is measured normal to *L* (Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Let the incident and refracted wavefronts propagate with normal velocities $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ respectively, and let them make the dihedral angles *θ*1 and *θ*2 respectively with the interface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] But the dihedral angle between two planes is also the angle between their normals.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] So *θ*1 is the angle between the normal to the incident wavefront and the normal to the interface, while *θ*2 is the angle between the normal to the refracted wavefront and the normal to the interface; and Eq.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] (**1**) tells us that the sines of these angles are in the same ratio as the respective velocities.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] This result has the form of "Snell's law", except that we have not yet said that the ratio of velocities is constant, nor identified *θ*1 and *θ*2 with the angles of incidence and refraction (called *θ*i and *θ*t above).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Obviously the angle of refraction cannot exceed 90°.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] In the limiting case, we put *θ*2 = 90° and *θ*1 = *θ*c in Eq.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] In deriving this result, we retain the assumption of isotropic media in order to identify *θ*1 and *θ*2 with the angles of incidence and refraction.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For electromagnetic waves, and especially for light, it is customary to express the above results in terms of *refractive indices*.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The refractive index of a medium with normal velocity $v_{1}$ is defined as $n_{1}=c/v_{1},$ where *c* is the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] (**3**) and (**4**) together describe the behavior in Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The arcsin function yielding *θ*c is defined only if *n*2 ≤ *n*1 $(v_{2}\geq v_{1}).$ Hence, for isotropic media, total internal reflection cannot occur if the second medium has a higher refractive index (lower normal velocity) than the first.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For example, there cannot be TIR for incidence from air to water; rather, the critical angle for incidence from water to air is the angle of refraction at grazing incidence from air to water (Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The medium with the higher refractive index is commonly described as optically *denser*, and the one with the lower refractive index as optically *rarer*.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Hence it is said that total internal reflection is possible for "dense-to-rare" incidence, but not for "rare-to-dense" incidence.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] When standing beside an aquarium with one's eyes below the water level, one is likely to see fish or submerged objects reflected in the water-air surface (Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The brightness of the reflected image – just as bright as the "direct" view – can be startling.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] A similar effect can be observed by opening one's eyes while swimming just below the water's surface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] If the water is calm, the surface outside the critical angle (measured from the vertical) appears mirror-like, reflecting objects below.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The region above the water cannot be seen except overhead, where the hemispherical field of view is compressed into a conical field known as *Snell's window*, whose angular diameter is twice the critical angle (cf.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The field of view above the water is theoretically 180° across, but seems less because as we look closer to the horizon, the vertical dimension is more strongly compressed by the refraction; e.g., by Eq.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] (**3**), for air-to-water incident angles of 90°, 80°, and 70°, the corresponding angles of refraction are 48.6° (*θcr* in Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] 6), 47.6°, and 44.8°, indicating that the image of a point 20° above the horizon is 3.8° from the edge of Snell's window‍ while the image of a point 10° above the horizon is only 1° from the edge.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] 7, for example, is a photograph taken near the bottom of the shallow end of a swimming pool.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] What looks like a broad horizontal stripe on the right-hand wall‍ consists of the lower edges of a row of orange tiles, and their reflections; this marks the water level, which can then be traced across the other wall.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The swimmer has disturbed the surface above her, scrambling the lower half of her reflection, and distorting the reflection of the ladder (to the right).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] But most of the surface is still calm, giving a clear reflection of the tiled bottom of the pool.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The space above the water is not visible except at the top of the frame, where the handles of the ladder are just discernible above the edge of Snell's window – within which the reflection of the bottom of the pool is only partial, but still noticeable in the photograph.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] One can even discern the color-fringing of the edge of Snell's window, due to variation of the refractive index, hence of the critical angle, with wavelength (see *Dispersion*).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The critical angle influences the angles at which gemstones are cut.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The round "brilliant" cut, for example, is designed to refract light incident on the front facets, reflect it twice by TIR off the back facets, and transmit it out again through the front facets, so that the stone looks bright.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] 8) is especially suitable for this treatment, because its high refractive index (about 2.42) and consequently small critical angle (about 24.5°) yield the desired behavior over a wide range of viewing angles.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Mathematically, waves are described in terms of time-varying fields, a "field" being a function of location in space.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] A propagating wave requires an "effort" field and a "flow" field, the latter being a vector (if we are working in two or three dimensions).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The product of effort and flow is related to power (see *System equivalence*).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For example, for sound waves in a non-viscous fluid, we might take the effort field as the pressure (a scalar), and the flow field as the fluid velocity (a vector).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The product of these two is intensity (power per unit area).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For electromagnetic waves, we shall take the effort field as the electric field **E** , and the flow field as the magnetizing field **H**.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Both of these are vectors, and their vector product is again the intensity (see *Poynting vector*).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] When a wave in (say) medium 1 is reflected off the interface between medium 1 and medium 2, the flow field in medium 1 is the vector sum of the flow fields due to the incident and reflected waves.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Hence, even if the reflection is total, there must be some penetration of the flow field into medium 2; and this, in combination with the laws relating the effort and flow fields, implies that there will also be some penetration of the effort field.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The same continuity condition implies that the variation ("waviness") of the field in medium 2 will be synchronized with that of the incident and reflected waves in medium 1.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] But, if the reflection is total, the spatial penetration of the fields into medium 2 must be limited somehow, or else the total extent and hence the total energy of those fields would continue to increase, draining power from medium 1.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Total reflection of a continuing wavetrain permits some energy to be stored in medium 2, but does not permit a *continuing* transfer of power from medium 1 to medium 2.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The incident wave is assumed to be plane and sinusoidal.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The reflected wave, for simplicity, is not shown.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The evanescent wave travels to the right in lock-step with the incident and reflected waves, but its amplitude falls off with increasing distance from the interface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] (Two features of the evanescent wave in Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] If the internal reflection is to be total, there must be no diversion of the evanescent wave.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Suppose, for example, that electromagnetic waves incident from glass (with a higher refractive index) to air (with a lower refractive index) at a certain angle of incidence are subject to TIR.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] And suppose that we have a third medium (often identical to the first) whose refractive index is sufficiently high that, if the third medium were to replace the second, we would get a standard transmitted wavetrain for the same angle of incidence.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] As the amplitude of the evanescent wave decays across the air gap, the transmitted waves are attenuated, so that there is less transmission, and therefore more reflection, than there would be with no gap; but as long as there is *some* transmission, the reflection is less than total.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] This phenomenon is called *frustrated total internal reflection* (where "frustrated" negates "total"), abbreviated "frustrated TIR" or "FTIR".
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Frustrated TIR can be observed by looking into the top of a glass of water held in one's hand (Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] If the glass is held loosely, contact may not be sufficiently close and widespread to produce a noticeable effect.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] But if it is held more tightly, the ridges of one's fingerprints interact strongly with the evanescent waves, allowing the ridges to be seen through the otherwise totally reflecting glass-air surface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The same effect can be demonstrated with microwaves, using paraffin wax as the "internal" medium (where the incident and reflected waves exist).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] In this case the permitted gap width might be (e.g.) 1 cm or several cm, which is easily observable and adjustable.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The term *frustrated TIR* also applies to the case in which the evanescent wave is scattered by an object sufficiently close to the reflecting interface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] This effect, together with the strong dependence of the amount of scattered light on the distance from the interface, is exploited in *total internal reflection microscopy*.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The mechanism of FTIR is called *evanescent-wave coupling*, and is a good analog to visualize quantum tunneling.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Due to the wave nature of matter, an electron has a non-zero probability of "tunneling" through a barrier, even if classical mechanics would say that its energy is insufficient.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Similarly, due to the wave nature of light, a photon has a non-zero probability of crossing a gap, even if ray optics would say that its approach is too oblique.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The consequent less-than-total reflection is called *attenuated total reflectance* (ATR).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] This effect, and especially the frequency-dependence of the absorption, can be used to study the composition of an unknown external medium.
