[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Hence, speaking loosely, we tend to say that the evanescent wave amplitude is significant within "a few wavelengths" of the interface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Between 1817 and 1823, Augustin-Jean Fresnel discovered that total internal reflection is accompanied by a non-trivial phase shift (that is, a phase shift that is not restricted to 0° or 180°), as the Fresnel reflection coefficient acquires a non-zero imaginary part.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] We shall now explain this effect for electromagnetic waves in the case of linear, homogeneous, isotropic, non-magnetic media.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The phase shift turns out to be an *advance*, which grows as the incidence angle increases beyond the critical angle, but which depends on the polarization of the incident wave.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] So a phase *advance* is equivalent to multiplication by a complex constant with a *negative* argument.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] This becomes more obvious when (e.g.) the field (**5**) is factored as $\mathbf {E_{k}} e^{i\mathbf {k\cdot r} }e^{-i\omega t},$ where the last factor contains the time dependence.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For each component of polarization, the incident, reflected, or transmitted electric field (**E** in Eq.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] (**5**)) has a certain direction and can be represented by its (complex) scalar component in that direction.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] The reflection or transmission coefficient can then be defined as a *ratio* of complex components at the same point, or at infinitesimally separated points on opposite sides of the interface.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] But, in order to fix the *signs* of the coefficients, we must choose positive senses for the "directions".
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For the *s* components, the obvious choice is to say that the positive directions of the incident, reflected, and transmitted fields are all the same (e.g., the z direction in Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For the *p* components, this article adopts the convention that the positive directions of the incident, reflected, and transmitted fields are inclined towards the same medium (that is, towards the same side of the interface, e.g. like the red arrows in Fig.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] But the reader should be warned that some books use a different convention for the *p* components, causing a different sign in the resulting formula for the reflection coefficient.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For the *s* polarization, let the reflection and transmission coefficients be rs and ts respectively.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For the *p* polarization, let the corresponding coefficients be rp and tp .
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Now we suppose that the transmitted wave is evanescent.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Making the same substitution in (**14**), we find that ts has the same denominator as rs with a positive real numerator (instead of a complex conjugate numerator) and therefore has *half* the argument of *rs*, so that *the phase advance of the evanescent wave is half that of the reflected wave*.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Making the same substitution in (**16**), we again find that the phase advance of the evanescent wave is *half* that of the reflected wave.
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] Equations (**17**) and (**18**) apply when *θ*c ≤ *θ*i < 90°, where *θ*i is the angle of incidence, and *θ*c is the critical angle arcsin (1/*n*).
[src:geometric-optics/total-internal-reflection-p01] For *θ*i ≤ *θ*c, the reflection coefficients are given by equations (**13**) and (**15**) and are *real*, so that the phase shift is either 0° (if the coefficient is positive) or 180° (if the coefficient is negative).
